nity—elderly Muscovite recipients, Russian aid workers, African student volunteers, and North American and European donors and volunteers—provide forms of social support that are highly valued and ultimately far more important than material resources. In Not by Bread Alone we see how the soup kitchens become sites of social stability and refuge for all who interact there—not just those with limited financial means—and how Muscovites articulate definitions of hunger and poverty that depend far more on the extent of one’s social contacts than on material factors.By rethinking the ways in which relationships between social and economic practices are theorized—by identifying social relations and social status as Russia’s true economic currency—this book challenges prevailing ideas about the role of the state, the nature of poverty and welfare, the feasibility of Western-style reforms, and the primacy of social connections in the daily lives of ordinary people in post-Soviet Russia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFood reliefzRussia (Federation). 0aPoorzRussia (Federation). 0aSocial networkszRussia (Federation). 0aSoup kitchenszRussia (Federation)zMoscow. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acharity.  achristian church of moscow.  aeconomic policies.  aethnographic study.  aethnography.  ahunger.  ainternational food aid.  amaterial needs.  amodern russia.  amoscow.  amuscovites.  anew russia.  anonfiction.  apost soviet russia.  apostsocialist world.  apoverty.  arefuge.  arussia.  arussian aid workers.  asocial currency.  asocial practices.  asocial relationships.  asocial status.  asocial support.  asocial welfare.  asoup kitchens.  astudents and teachers.  avolunteers.  awelfare.  awestern reform.08iTit